rican writers who fled to Europe to escape Anglo-American provincialism, refugees from fascism, wandering surrealists, and displaced communists all contributed to the proliferation of print. Yet the little magazine was equally crucial to literary production and consumption in the postcolonial world, where it helped connect newly independent African nations. Bulson concludes with reflections on the digitization of these defunct little magazines and what it means for our ongoing desire to understand modernism's global dimensions in the past and its digital afterlife.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCriticism. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryy20th century. 0aLittle magazinesxHistoryx21st century. 0aLittle magazinesxHistoryy19th centuryvPeriodicals. 0aLittle magazinesxHistoryy20th centuryvPeriodicals. 0aLittle magazinesxHistoryy20th century. 0aLittle magazinesxHistoryy21st century. 0aLittle magazinesxHistory. 0aLittle magazinesxPeriodicalsxHistoryx19th century. 0aLittle magazinesxPeriodicalsxHistoryx20th century. 0aModernism (Literature) 0aModernism (Literature). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063857808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2016z9783110485332oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/buls1797640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231542326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231542326.jpg  a978-3-11-063857-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL 